SIMPLE: stucco
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stucco
<hw>Stuc"co</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Stuccoes</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>, <plw>Stuccos</plw>.</plu> <ety>[It.,
fr. OHG. <ets>stucchi</ets> a crust, piece, G. <ets>st⟦uum⟧ck</ets>
piece; akin to AS. <ets>stycce</ets>. See <er>Stock</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Plaster of any kind used as a coating for walls,
especially, a fine plaster, composed of lime or gypsum with sand and
pounded marble, used for internal decorations and fine work.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Work made of stucco; stuccowork.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stucco</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stucco
<hw>Stuc"co</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Stuccoed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Stuccoing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To overlay or
decorate with stucco, or fine plaster.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stuccoer</ent>⟦br⟧
